content: The largest 'bluestone' at Stonehenge, weighing six tonnes, was transported from approximately 750 km away in Scotland, study stated. Chemical analysis was used to trace the stone's origins to the Orkney Islands in northeast Scotland. This finding contradicts earlier beliefs that bluestones came from Preseli Hills in Wales. The study added that it was moved by water rather than land.
title: Stonehenge's 6-tonne stone was transported from 750 km away: Study
bottom_headline: The study was published in Nature

content: Archaeologists have discovered four human remains believed to be between 3,100 and 3,800 years old on a land in Peru that appears to have housed a ceremonial temple. The remains were found nestled between mud and stone walls. Feren Castillo, an archaeologist at the National University of Trujillo in Peru, said there could be more buried remains in the area.
title: 4 human remains up to 3,800 years old unearthed in Peruvian temple

content: Paleontologists at Tsukuba University have identified a new extinct walrus-like mammal, Ontocetus posti, from Lower Pleistocene deposits in the North Atlantic. Discovered in Norwich and Antwerp, Ontocetus posti displays feeding adaptations similar to modern walruses. The species was initially misidentified as Ontocetus emmonsi but has distinct dental features that set it apart as new species.
title: Extinct walrus-like mammal discovered in the North Atlantic

content: A research shows that wild birds like ducks and crows living near humans, particularly in cities, carry bacteria with antimicrobial resistance (AMR). These urban birds possess up to three times more AMR genes, including resistance to common antibiotics like fluoroquinolones and beta-lactams, than those in isolated areas. This poses risks to human health, agriculture, and animals.
title: City birds can be carriers of antibiotic-resistant bacteria: Study
bottom_headline: Study was conducted by Ineos Oxford Institute

content: State Bank of India has hiked its marginal cost of funds based lending rate (MCLR) by 10 basis points across all tenors. content: NASA recently photographed Earth's terminator, the line dividing night from day. This moving boundary is visible from space and marks where sunlight meets darkness due to Earth's rotation. The terminator shifts across the planet twice daily, defining sunrise and sunset, while creating extended periods of daylight or darkness at the poles. It creates effects like midnight sun in polar regions.
title: What is Earth's terminator, recently photographed by NASA?
bottom_headline: It moves at around 1,670 kmph at equator

content: In Nebraska's Monowi, the world's smallest village, Elsie Eiler is its sole resident. The village was home to 123 people in 1930 with the population dwindling over the years. In 2000, Elsie and her husband, Rudy, were the only residents with the latter passing away in 2004. A survey in 2020 recorded 86-year-old Elsie as the sole resident of Monowi.
title: Nebraska's Monowi village has only one resident since 2004

content: The Nassak Diamond, originating from India's Kollur Mines in Golconda, is also known as the 'Eye' of Lord Shiva. It was once mounted on the crown of Lord Shiva at the Trimbakeshwar Temple, Nashik, one of the 12 Jyotirlingas. After the Anglo-Maratha War, the diamond fell into the hands of the British and now is owned by a Lebanese billionaire.
title: Nassak Diamond once adorned Lord Shiva's crown at Maha temple

content: Sweden has recorded the first case of a contagious new variant of mpox outside the African continent. The news comes after WHO declared mpox a global public health emergency for the second time in two years.
title: Sweden reports 1st case of new mpox variant outside Africa
